title: For Sale:  1898 Iver Johnson .32 revolver
location: White Bear Lake, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Iver Johnson 2nd model .32 revolver.  
My father acquired this gun in 1977 in lieu of payment due him for Locksmith services.  It was locked in the safe until last October when he passed away.  It now belongs to me but even though I have a lot of firearms, I have no interest in this one.  Manufactured in 1898, it is the 2nd model with the double post top latch, free-wheeling cylinder, and leaf spring under the grips.  Serial number is located on the frame and starts with the letter "E".  The left grip is original but the right grip was fashioned out of wood.  I have seen original grips on ebay.  
I am no expert on antique firearms but I've been told by those who claim they are that the nickle finish appears to be above average for it's age.  Mechanically, everything works fine.  The cylinder is tight when locked into position and the ejector is nice and smooth.  The trigger pull is smooth and fairly light.  Other than that, I have no knowledge about this gun.  I'm not going to blow smoke up your butt and tell you it once belonged to Ma Barker or John Dillinger.  No research has been done by me.
I also do not know what the value is.  One collector said it was worth around $300 but that's one opinion.  Dad said he did have it appraised in 1979 for $215 but then again, that is one persons estimate of value.  Therefore, I am putting it online for $275 or "Best Offer". Being it was manufactured prior to 1899 it is a legal antique.  No FFL required to purchase.  Feel free to ask questions or request more pictures and thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Model 1917, Eddystone, (Subsidiary of Remington) "The American Enfield"  sporterized rifle,  Cal. 300 H&H Magnum, excellent condition.  Serial No. 517889
postcontent:
This is an excellent example of a almost mint condition sporteriizied  M1917 Eddystone rifle.  Eddystone was the arsenal in Eddystone PA where this rifle was originally made ,,the model 1917 and was a retooled 30-06.  The barrel length is 24 inches long and the bore is excellent. The stock is in great shape with almost no wear.  When the U.S. entered the war, it had a similar need for rifles. The Springfield Armory had delivered approximately 843,000 1903 rifles, but due to the difficulties in production, rather than re-tool the Pattern 14 factories to produce the standard U.S. rifle, the M1903 Springfield, it was realized that it would be much quicker to adapt the British design for the U.S. .30-06 cartridge, for which it was well-suited. Accordingly, Remington Arms Co. altered the design for caliber .30-06, under the close supervision of the U.S. Army Ordnance Department, which was formally adopted as the U.S. Rifle, Caliber .30, Model of 1917. In addition to Remington's production at Ilion, New York and Eddystone, Pennsylvania, Winchester produced the rifle at their New Haven, Connecticut plant, a combined total more than twice the 1903's production, and was the unofficial service rifle. Eddystone made 1,181,908 rifles - more than the production of Remington (545,541 rifles) and Winchester (465,980 rifles) combined.
Design changes were few; the magazine, bolt face, chamber and rifling dimensions were altered to suit the .30-06 cartridge and the volley fire sights on the left side of the weapon were deleted. The markings were changed to reflect the model and caliber change. A 16.5-inch blade bayonet, the M1917 Bayonet was produced for use on the rifle. It would later be used on several other small arms like the Winchester M12 trench shotgun and early M1 Garands.
The new rifle was used alongside the M1903 Springfield rifle and quickly surpassed the Springfield design in numbers produced and units issued. By November 11, 1918 about 75% of the AEF in France were armed with M1917s.  Some American soldiers disliked the greater weight and more fragile ejector of the M1917 and favored the M1903 Springfield.
An M1917 Enfield rifle was used by Sergeant Alvin York on October 8, 1918, during the event that would see him awarded the Medal of Honor. 
After the armistice, the M1917 rifles were placed in storage for the most part, although Chemical Mortar units continued to be issued them. During the 1920s and 1930s a large number of M1917 rifles were released for civilian use through the NRA or were sold as surplus. Many were sporterized, sometimes including rechambering to more powerful magnum hunting cartridges, such as .300 H&H Magnum and .300 Winchester Magnum. It was so popular as a sporting weapon that Remington manufactured about 30,000 new rifles as the Model 30 from 1921 to 1940.
